\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{Step 1: Define Variables}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Let \(t\) be the time (in seconds) of the race.
    \item Since Team B finishes 10 seconds before Team A, Team B's race time is \(t - 10\) seconds.
    \item Team A starts 30 seconds before Team B, so Team A's total race time is:
    \[
    t + 30 \, \text{seconds.}
    \]
    \item Let \(d\) be the total distance of the race.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Step 2: Set Up Equations}
We know:
\[
d = \frac{1}{50} \left( t + 30 \right) \quad \text{(Team A's distance formula)}
\]
\[
d = \frac{1}{40} \left( t - 10 \right) \quad \text{(Team B's distance formula)}
\]

\subsection*{Step 3: Set Distances Equal}
Since both teams cover the same distance:
\[
\frac{1}{50} \left( t + 30 \right) = \frac{1}{40} \left( t - 10 \right)
\]
\[
t + 30 = \frac{5}{4}t - \frac{1}{4} \times 10
\]
\[
t + 30 = \frac{5}{4}t - \frac{5}{4}
\]
\[\frac{1}{4}t = 35
\]
\[
t = 140 \, \text{seconds.}
\]

\subsection*{Step 4: Calculate Distances}
Now that we know \(t = 140\) seconds, we calculate the distances:
\[
d = \frac{1}{50} \times 170 = 3.4 \, \text{laps (Team A's distance)}
